 {"id":"br-r37-c1-h41f2","title":"parity: isomorphism match helper functions missing","description":"NetworkX exposes categorical_node_match, categorical_edge_match, categorical_multiedge_match, numerical_node_match, numerical_edge_match, numerical_multiedge_match, generic_node_match, generic_edge_match, and generic_multiedge_match from networkx.algorithms.isomorphism. FrankenNetworkX does not export these helpers, so callback construction for GraphMatcher and is_isomorphic differs. Add wrappers delegating to networkx.algorithms.isomorphism and parity tests covering node/edge/multiedge helper behavior.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"cod-networkx","created_at":"2026-04-25T09:19:58.209906853Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T09:24:21.965842231Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T09:24:21.963986187Z","close_reason":"Completed in bc5cd31","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-hq5pq","title":"parity: connectivity minimum_st_edge_cut missing","description":"networkx.algorithms.connectivity.minimum_st_edge_cut(G, s, t, flow_func=None, auxiliary=None, residual=None) returns minimum st edge cut. Not exposed by franken_networkx (only minimum_edge_cut and minimum_st_node_cut exist). Add Python wrapper delegating to networkx and export at top-level.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-25T11:59:43.139262003Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T03:15:05.326488163Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T03:15:05.324637730Z","close_reason":"Already implemented in fnx — top-level export matches nx.connectivity exactly. Landed tests/python/test_connectivity_parity_extras.py (commit 3765516) with 37 cases freezing the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-hz9k5","title":"parity: drawing wrappers (draw, draw_networkx, draw_networkx_*, display) collapse nx's per-arg signature into generic *args, **kwargs","description":"fnx.draw_networkx, fnx.draw_networkx_nodes, fnx.draw_networkx_edges, fnx.draw_networkx_labels, fnx.draw_networkx_edge_labels, fnx.display all wrap nx via _delegate_draw with generic (G, *args, **kwargs) signature. inspect.signature returns the catch-all instead of nx's documented surface (e.g. nx.draw_networkx_edges has 18 keyword params). Same root cause as approximation namespace fix (functools.wraps). draw also has the variadic-kwarg-name drift (kwargs vs nx's kwds). Fix: apply functools.wraps(nx_func) to each wrapper. Add parity test that asserts inspect.signature(fnx.X) matches inspect.signature(nx.X) for the full drawing namespace.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T05:08:06.159041751Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T05:10:36.083919851Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T05:10:36.082061192Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit c36f08f. Drawing wrappers now use _wrap_nx_drawing helper that applies functools.wraps(nx_func) to each delegator. inspect.signature(fnx.draw_networkx_edges) returns the full 18-parameter nx surface. 18 parity tests in test_drawing_signature_parity.py freeze the contract (signature match + namespace check + metadata).","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-j2vof","title":"parity: G.nodes(data=...) returns NodeView (or list), nx returns NodeDataView","description":"fnx Graph.nodes(data=True) returns the rust NodeView (class 'NodeView') whereas nx returns a 'NodeDataView'. fnx Graph.nodes(data='attr') returns a Python list whereas nx returns a 'NodeDataView'. Both deviate from nx's class-name contract — drop-in code doing isinstance(v, nx.classes.reportviews.NodeDataView) fails. The list case also breaks live-view semantics (mutations after the view is captured are not reflected). Same root cause and same fix as br-r37-c1-sf1ku (EdgeDataView): introduce a NodeDataView wrapper that re-invokes node_view_call on each access (iter/len/contains/repr) with class name aligned to nx.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T08:13:54.593945959Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T08:19:42.523438417Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T08:19:42.521368266Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 298400a. G.nodes(data=True) and G.nodes(data='attr') now return a live NodeDataView wrapper that re-fetches on each access, matching nx's contract. 13 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-j6qpf","title":"parity: draw_bipartite signature divergence — fnx requires top_nodes positionally, nx accepts only **kwargs","description":"fnx.draw_bipartite has signature (G, top_nodes, pos=None, **kwds) where top_nodes is a required positional arg, but networkx.drawing.nx_pylab.draw_bipartite has (G, **kwargs). Drop-in calls like nx.draw_bipartite(G) work in nx but fnx raises TypeError missing positional argument top_nodes. Fix: align signature to (G, **kwargs) and pull top_nodes out of kwargs (or compute it via bipartite_sets if absent), so fnx accepts the same call shape as nx.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T04:28:46.975023293Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T04:49:45.891385685Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T04:49:45.889512479Z","close_reason":"Shipped in 097c007: draw_bipartite now (G, **kwargs) matching nx; top_nodes pulled from kwargs and inferred via bipartite_sets if absent. 170 smoke tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-lb47c","title":"parity: Graph class methods used wrong param names (node vs n, bunch vs ebunch) + has_edge had extra key on simple Graph","description":"fnx Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph/MultiDiGraph class methods used wrong parameter names: has_node(node) vs nx has_node(n); neighbors(node) vs neighbors(n); remove_node(node) vs remove_node(n); remove_edges_from(bunch) vs remove_edges_from(ebunch); MG.remove_nodes_from(*) vs nodes. Also Graph.has_edge had key=None which only belongs on MultiGraph. Drop-in callers using kwarg form (G.has_node(n=x)) hit TypeError. Fixed: renamed all wrappers to nx names. Split _private_aware_has_edge into _simple (Graph/DiGraph: u,v) and _multi (MG/MDG: u,v,key=None) variants. 12 parity tests freeze the contract.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T05:00:46.545653530Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T05:05:28.418051592Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T05:05:28.416193976Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 1183506. Class method signatures match nx exactly: has_node(n)/neighbors(n), Graph.has_edge(u,v) (no key), MG.has_edge(u,v,key=None). 12 parity tests in test_graph_class_method_signature_parity.py freeze the contract. Also reverted graph_edit_distance/optimize_edit_paths timeout to raise NetworkXNotImplemented per project no-fallback policy.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-lby4x","title":"parity: isolates() returns list_iterator, nx returns generator (eager vs lazy evaluation)","description":"fnx.isolates(G) returns a list_iterator (Rust binding materializes the full list eagerly) while nx.isolates(G) returns a generator (lazy). Behavioral drift: code doing isinstance(result, types.GeneratorType) breaks; lazy short-circuits like next(isolates(huge_graph)) materialize the entire node set on fnx vs. one node on nx. Fix: thin Python wrapper that delegates to the Rust impl via 'yield from' so the returned object is a true generator.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T05:44:38.565317140Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T05:46:20.491389089Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T05:46:20.489589242Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit ea4a271. fnx.isolates(G) now returns a true generator matching nx's contract. 8 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
